The dissonance of an industry that claims to be progressive (ostensibly celebrating body positivity and survivors) and then reveres figures like Lagerfeld without even acknowledging their regressive views, perfectly encapsulates the problem. 

Read my op-ed in full @thedailybeast via the link in my story. #MetGala #MayDay #FashionWorkersAct

“Most models are manipulated by agencies to sign contracts while being told that they will become ‘stars’ when in reality statistics show that models are thrown into exorbitant debt because there are no legal safety nets or protection in the modeling industry,” former top modeling agent Carolyn Kramer told @byemilystmartin @latimes. “Change is long overdue, and I’m proud to stand with the Model Alliance in support of the Fashion Workers Act.”

Kudos, Carolyn, and thank you for your support! Full article via the link in my story. Photo: @reedyoung

This week, the Writers Guild of America went on strike as contract negotiations came to an impasse. The Model Alliance supports the WGA, and we urge studios to meet their demands now.

Today, I joined fellow survivor advocates outside the NYC Civil Courthouse in solidarity with @ejeancarroll1, who, thanks to the #AdultSurvivorsAct, is seeking justice against her abuser, former President Donald Trump.

All of us standing here today worked hard to make sure that abusers and those who enabled them are held accountable. It’s certainly not easy, and I want to thank E. Jean Carroll for her tenacity and bravery through this process.

Regardless of the verdict in Carroll’s case, all survivors deserve to have their day in court. That’s why @modelallianceny was proud to join with @safehorizon, the organizer of today’s press conference, in championing the Adult Survivors Act, which opened a one-year window for survivors of sexual abuse to file suit in New York, no matter how long ago the abuse happened.

The lookback window created by the Adult Survivors Act will close on Nov. 23, 2023. With only six months left, we encourage survivors in the fashion industry who are interested in exploring their options to contact our safe, confidential support line. 

📷 Rob Dicker

Yesterday, @modelallianceny joined with Senator @bradhoylman and @freelancersu @rlespinal to call on lawmakers to pass the #FashionWorkersAct before the legislative session ends on 6/8. This bill would bring predatory management companies into regulation for the first time and establish basic labor protections for models and content creators working in NY’s fashion industry.

Thank you to our speakers @nidhisunil @iammarimalek @alexshanklin @robynlawley and @kennysale, and to all the worker leaders who joined us in Albany and shared their stories with lawmakers. Your leadership is what makes this possible. 

Learn more about the Fashion Workers Act and sign our petition at the link in my story.

The @modelallianceny and @saraziff have been working with NY lawmakers to pass a bill that would regulate modeling agencies.

The Fashion Workers Act would provide models and content creators with protections that Ziff sees as basic, essential, and maddeningly overdue. However, as I exclusively report in my newsletter Back Row, a group of six agencies calling itself the Coalition for Fairness in Fashion has banded together to stop the current bill from passing.

“There is zero financial transparency, and there’s also no obligation for the agency to act even in your interests,” said Ziff. “That’s some Britney Spears shit. When we’ve been meeting with lawmakers, they’re shocked. They’ve never heard of that before in any other industry.”

These financial arrangements, Ziff argues, beget sexual exploitation and human trafficking. “Just think about the most prominent people in the #MeToo movement, whether it was Bill Cosby or Jeffrey Epstein or Harvey Weinstein,” she said. “The common denominator is they were all preying on girls who wanted to work as models.”

Tap the link in bio to read the full story in Back Row.

As we reflect on this year’s legislative session, we have a lot to be proud of. Together, we’ve made significant progress, but our work isn’t over.

Yesterday, for the first time, the NY Senate recognized the need to extend labor protections to models and content creators and passed the #FashionWorkersAct 46-16. We thank Senator @bradhoylman for his leadership, and Majority Leader @andreastewartcousins for bringing our bill to the floor. We also thank Assemblymember @karinesreyes87, who worked to build support in her chamber. While we ultimately did not receive a vote in the Assembly this year, we were proud to pick up 24 new co-sponsors this session.

Our progress wouldn’t be possible without our community of models, content creators, creative artists, and allies joining forces to create a better fashion industry. Thank you to our Worker Council, who volunteered their time, energy and stories to inspire meaningful change despite pushback from the industry, to our growing list of endorsers including @cfda @freelancersu @safehorizon @melkenyc and many others, to @chris.smalls_ and @rlespinal for doubling down in solidarity, and to every person who joined our call to action to make this bill law.

​​The Fashion Workers Act recognizes that every person who works for a living deserves to be treated with dignity and respect; models and content creators who are the faces of New York’s multi-billion dollar fashion industry should not be an exception. Our work isn’t over, and with your support, we’ll be back to get the Fashion Workers Act over the finish line next session.

Four years ago I met a guy on a tiny train platform in the middle of nowhere. Exactly one year later we got married here, and today we made our annual pilgrimage back to our spot with our babies (one furry, one human) in tow. Happy 3rd wedding anniversary, @reedyoung.

Like actors, fashion workers are struggling for professional dignity behind a veil of glamour and prestige. And, because the fashion industry infamously lacks regulatory oversight, fashion workers are much further behind than actors and writers in the entertainment industry.

Unlike actors, current law is unclear on whether models can legally unionize in the US. Models are most often considered independent contractors, and independent contractors are prohibited from unionizing. Because of this, @modelallianceny is pursuing alternative forms of advocacy and organizing to improve our working conditions – leading to the introduction of the #FashionWorkersAct in NY. 

Read more via @voguebusiness at the link in my story.

Today, the tiny newborn that I brought home from the hospital approximately two blinks ago is moving on from daycare to preschool! Graduation tears were much sweeter than first day of daycare tears when I left looking like a panda (don’t wear mascara while dropping off your infant with strangers). 

Gus (or “Gussy,” as your friends and teachers — the wonderful women whose work makes my work possible — call you), you are growing more capable and curious every day. And we are so proud of you ❤️

This Labor Day weekend, I hope you’ll consider pitching in towards @modelallianceny’s $20,000 grassroots fundraising goal. The first $5,000 raised will be matched dollar for dollar by @cordesfdn! 

Every day, we assist workers through our free, confidential support line with issues such as debt bondage, sexual exploitation, and racial discrimination – all while working to address and prevent these issues through legislative reform. Your support is really what makes our work possible (link in bio).

This #LaborDay, we’re calling in our community to help @modelallianceny raise $20K by midnight – and we’re already halfway there. Make your tax-deductible gift today to help us reach our goal! (link in bio).

Last week at @FordFoundation’s inaugural #FreeFuture forum, I joined Sarita Gupta, Vice President of U.S. Programs at Ford, and Ellen McGirt, Senior Editor at Fortune Magazine, for a conversation on gender-based violence at work. 

At @modelallianceny, we’re working to prevent gender-based violence from happening in our industry through the #FashionWorkersAct, a NYS bill that would extend workers rights to our community of workers — mostly young, immigrant women. 

Thank you, @FordFoundation @cindi_leive for bringing together an awesome group of movement leaders. 

Watch the forum via the link in my story. #UNGAxFord

This Wednesday, 10/4, the Federal Trade Commission will hold a virtual roundtable discussion on the impact of generative artificial intelligence on creative fields. I plan to speak about key harms and ways generative AI may impact the @modelallianceny community and how we hope to address these harms the fashion industry. The event will be webcast live and also feature representatives from @sagaftra and @writersguildwest, among others. Join us and tune in!

This week, the Federal Trade Commission held a roundtable discussion, “Creative Economy and Generative AI,” to better understand the impact of generative AI on creative fields. I spoke on behalf of @modelallianceny and joined fellow panelists Duncan Crabtree-Ireland of @sagaftra, John August of @writersguildwest, John K. Painting of @afm_union and Umair Kazi of @authorsguild, among others. 

Thank you to the FTC for including us in this important and timely discussion. Watch the full roundtable via the link in my story.

The Abercrombie Guys: The Dark Side of Cool is available now on @bbciplayer in the U.K. and @bbcselect @appletv @primevideo @therokuchannel in the U.S. The one-hour documentary, featuring me and members of our community, including survivor advocate @barrettpall, chronicles @bbcnews’s two and a half year investigation into allegations of sexual exploitation by @abercrombie ex-CEO Mike Jeffries and his partner Matthew Smith. Male survivors say Jeffries hired a middleman to recruit them for events that involved performing sex acts and preyed on their aspirations of becoming a model for one of the most aspirational teen brands. 

Until November 23, 2023, the #AdultSurvivorsAct in New York gives survivors of sexual abuse a chance at justice no matter how long ago the abuse happened. If you or anyone you know is a survivor of sexual abuse by Jeffries or one of his affiliates, we at the @modelallianceny encourage you to act now by contacting our discreet support line, MA Support.

Survivors have 48 days left to file a civil suit against their abuser under the #AdultSurvivorsAct.

Many survivors of sexual abuse take years to report, only to find it’s too late to take action. Now, thanks to the Adult Survivors Act, there’s a pathway to pursue justice. With the window to file a lawsuit closing on November 23, now is the time to take action. 

Survivors in the fashion industry who are interested in exploring their options can contact @modelallianceny’s discreet support line, MA Support. Thank you @safehorizon for hosting us today, and @bradhoylman and @lindabrosenthal_67 for making this opportunity possible.

How was Abercrombie & Fitch an environment ripe for abuse? I sat down with BBC journalist @rianna_craxford to discuss this and more. Listen to “World of Secrets: The Abercrombie Guys,” a seven-part podcast series @bbcsounds via the link in my story.  

If you are a survivor of sexual abuse in the fashion industry, you can contact @modelallianceny’s discreet support line: modelalliance.org/support

Models & content creators: Join @modelallianceny on Thursday, 11/9, in NYC for “Navigating Representation Agreements.” 

We’ll be discussing how to navigate agency contracts, what the real-life implications are for industry standard agreements, and how to join our efforts to forge a fairer fashion industry. 

This event is free, and open to models and content creators. Food and drinks will be served.

Location will be provided with RSVP.

Until November 23, survivors of sexual abuse can file a civil case under New York’s #AdultSurvivorsAct. 

Survivors who are interested in exploring their options should act now by contacting @modelallianceny’s discreet support line, MA Support. Visit modelalliance.org/asa to learn more.

The #AdultSurvivorsAct gives survivors who were 18+ at the time of the abuse a chance at justice against their abuser and/or the institution that enabled the abuse, no matter how long ago it happened. Since the law took effect last year, 400+ cases have been filed across New York State – many of which represent multiple survivors – and that number continues to rise as the deadline approaches.

If you are a survivor of sexual abuse in the fashion industry, please reach out. You’re not alone, and you have a community @modelallianceny here to support you.

Thank you to everyone who joined @modelallianceny at yesterday’s event, Navigating Representation Agreements: How Models and Content Creators Can Protect Themselves and Help Forge a Fairer Fashion Industry. We were grateful for the opportunity to educate our community about agency contracts and their significant implications in light of the industry’s lack of regulation and deeply unequal power dynamic. 

“Fashion workers are unprotected outside whatever is written in their individual agency contracts, which is why it’s so important that people understand and feel comfortable with the contracts they are signing,” said our associate director @syddgio. “Our hope is if you’re just getting into the industry or thinking about signing a new contract, this conversation will help you.”

I encouraged the audience to get more involved with the Model Alliance and our campaign for the #FashionWorkersAct, which would increase transparency and protect models and content creators from unfair agency practices. We’re here to stand with you and support you. Together, we can create a more transparent, accountable, fun, and fair fashion industry.

Special thanks to Quinn Emanuel and Getman, Sweeney & Dunn for making this conversation possible. We look forward to sharing more takeaways and opportunities to get involved soon.

Photos: @reedyoung

Yesterday, @nidhisunil, who was named Vogue India’s Model of the Year in 2017 and recently became a global ambassador for L’Oreal Paris, and @riribibi_, a content creator who has worked for multiple brands including L’Oreal and Pantene, spoke at @modelallianceny’s event about their personal experiences navigating agency contracts.

Nidhi acknowledged that as a young immigrant, she felt she had no leverage to negotiate the terms of her contract when she signed with her first agency. However, as she worked to establish herself in the industry and forged a successful modeling career, she felt more confident about making demands and setting expectations with her agents around transparency. 

Riri recalled how excited and hopeful she felt signing a contract in 2020 with her first agency. She eventually discovered that the one-sided agreement left her vulnerable to wage theft: although she had agreed to a standard 20% agency commission, it turned out that her agency was actually taking 82% of her earnings. When it came time to sign with a new agency, Riri reached out to the Model Alliance for support and a referral to a trusted attorney to help negotiate her contract, and now feels confident in her representation. 

Special thanks to Quinn Emanuel and Getman, Sweeney & Dunn for making this conversation possible. We look forward to sharing more takeaways and opportunities to get involved soon.

Photos: @reedyoung

At @modelallianceny’s event last night, Elisabeth Schiffbauer, an attorney at @getmansweeneydunnlaw, and Chris Kercher, a partner at @quinnemanuel, shared best practices for entering and exiting an agency contract and how working with an attorney can help. 

Elisabeth explained how “just because something is ‘industry standard’ doesn’t mean it’s fair.” For example, she shared that agencies are normally granted power of attorney, yet they claim to have no fiduciary duty to the people they represent. They also typically have rights to exclusive representation, yet they have no obligation to book their talent jobs. She encouraged models and content creators to ask questions about their contracts and negotiate where they can.

Chris explained that terminating an agency contract can be difficult since most renew automatically at the end of their three-year term. He shared how models and content creators can get ahead of the renewal, and how an attorney may be able to help with early termination in cases where the agency isn’t fulfilling their basic obligations. 

Special thanks to Quinn Emanuel and Getman, Sweeney & Dunn for making this conversation possible. We look forward to sharing more takeaways and opportunities to get involved soon.

Photos: @reedyoung

Today, @modelallianceny joined lawmakers and advocates to announce the #SurvivorsJusticeAgenda, a package of legislation that will build on the #ChildVictimsAct and #AdultSurvivorsAct and put power back in the hands of survivors of sexual abuse in New York. 

“Trauma takes time, and our laws should reflect that by eliminating the statute of limitations on child sexual abuse,” said @shainadanziger, who recounted her experience of sexual assault by an agency-referred photographer at age 17. “It has taken 20 years for me to feel comfortable enough to speak up. For others, it could be even longer.”

Shaina also called for expanded access to justice for survivors of human trafficking: “We must open up a civil lookback window for survivors of sex trafficking, just like we did for survivors of child and adult sexual abuse, so that my peers who have had to suffer in silence like me are able to seek recourse in the courts,” she said.

Kudos, @shainadanziger @syddgio @bridiezfarrell @mpolenberg @ericaarden @lindabrosenthal_67 @bradhoylman @_juliasalazar and the entire survivor justice coalition. If you want to support our efforts at the Model Alliance, please consider making a donation via the link in my bio.

Anyone who has worked for social justice long enough knows that nothing worth fighting for comes easily – and the wins aren’t accomplished by any one person. Standing shoulder to shoulder with the fearless ones is how meaningful change happens. For anyone who appreciates how difficult it is to confront vested interests, I see you and hope you’ll join us @modelallianceny.

This profile is quite personal and I’m not used to being so vulnerable, but @eshugs made it easier. Thank you @nymag @thecut for sharing my story. 

And thanks to the long list of people who have and continue to be integral to this work, including my colleague @syddgio, our Board and Worker Council whose courage keeps me going, our champions in Albany, and all of our partners and allies. This piece is a window into my story, but this is OUR movement.

Also: I love that my pup, Tillie, made it into the piece.
